VALUES
(1, 10, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'between Nineveh and Calah', 10, 35, 'greek', 'Geographical Significance', 'While the Old Testament primarily uses Hebrew, the concept of ''between'' can be linked to the Greek word ἀνάμεσα (anamesa, G3032) which means ''between'' or ''in the midst of.'' This spatial relationship underscores the interconnectedness of cities in ancient civilizations. Understanding this term enriches our view of how geographic locations influenced trade, culture, and power dynamics.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3032", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term meaning ''between.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Mizraim begat Ludim, and Anamim, and Lehabim, and Naphtuhim,', 4, 64, 'connection', 'Mizraim''s Descendants', 'The mention of Mizraim (Egypt) and his descendants connects to Exodus 1:1-5, where the Israelites multiply in Egypt. This highlights the historical importance of Egypt in the biblical narrative as a place of both oppression and refuge. The names listed here foreshadow future interactions between these groups and the Israelites.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 1:1-5", "description": "Describes the Israelites'' growth in Egypt."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Mizraim begat Ludim, and Anamim, and Lehabim, and Naphtuhim,', 4, 64, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Lineage', 'This passage suggests that God orchestrates the descendants of nations, establishing their roles in salvation history. Many scholars believe that the genealogies in Genesis reveal God''s plan for humanity, emphasizing His sovereignty over nations and the unfolding of His redemptive purpose through history.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Mizraim begat Ludim, and Anamim, and Lehabim, and Naphtuhim,', 4, 64, 'greek', 'Significance of ''begat''', 'Though this is Hebrew text, the concept of ''begat'' can be related to the Greek ''γεννάω'' (gennao, G1080) - to beget, to bring forth. This term emphasizes the continuity of life and heritage, reflecting the importance of lineage in biblical narratives.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1080", "description": "Greek term for ''to beget''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Mizraim begat Ludim, and Anamim, and Lehabim, and Naphtuhim,', 4, 64, 'question', 'Understanding Generational Impact', 'What can we learn from the lineage of Mizraim in terms of our own spiritual heritage? How does recognizing our ancestors influence our understanding of identity and purpose in God''s plan?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Pathrusim, and Casluhim, (out of whom came Philistim,)', 4, 58, 'connection', 'Philistim''s Origin', 'The mention of the Philistim in this verse connects directly to their prominent role in the narratives of Israel''s history, particularly in the books of Judges and 1 Samuel. For instance, in Judges 3:3, the Philistines are identified as a significant adversary of Israel, showcasing the ongoing conflict between these two groups. Understanding their lineage helps clarify the historical context of these confrontations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Judges 3:3", "description": "This verse outlines the Philistines as part of Israel''s adversaries."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Pathrusim, and Casluhim, (out of whom came Philistim,)', 4, 58, 'theology', 'Understanding Lineage', 'This verse illustrates the importance of genealogies in Scripture, particularly in understanding God''s unfolding plan through specific lineages. Many scholars believe that the inclusion of these names emphasizes God''s sovereignty over nations and peoples, highlighting how His purposes can emerge from unexpected sources. This resonates with the broader biblical theme of redemption and God''s use of all nations in His plan.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theological significance of genealogies in Scripture."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Philistim,)', 47, 58, 'question', 'Reflecting on Adversaries', 'What does the mention of the Philistim in this genealogy reveal about God''s plan even in opposition? As adversaries of Israel, they played a crucial role in shaping the faith and character of God''s people. How can we view challenges and adversaries in our lives as part of God''s greater narrative?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Canaan begat Sidon his firstborn', 4, 36, 'connection', 'Canaan''s Lineage Significance', 'The mention of Canaan begetting Sidon highlights the importance of lineage in biblical narratives. This is echoed in Joshua 11:3, where the Canaanites are called upon in the context of Israel''s conquest. Recognizing Sidon as Canaan''s firstborn emphasizes the historical and territorial significance of the Phoenicians, descendants of Sidon, in biblical history. This connection sheds light on the cultural interactions between the Israelites and their neighbors.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Joshua 11:3", "description": "The Canaanites'' role in Israel''s conquest."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Canaan begat Sidon his firstborn', 4, 36, 'theology', 'Understanding Cursed Lineage', 'The genealogy presented here underscores a theological theme of judgment and consequence. Many scholars believe that Canaan''s lineage, marked by the curse of Noah (Genesis 9:25), reflects the broader implications of sin and its effects on nations. This passage suggests that the descendants of Canaan were destined for conflict with Israel, illustrating how familial and national identities can bear the weight of ancestral actions.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 9:25", "description": "The curse of Canaan as a foundational element."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'Canaan begat Sidon his firstborn', 4, 36, 'question', 'Impact of Lineage on Identity', 'How does understanding the lineage of Canaan and his descendants, particularly Sidon, shape your understanding of identity in Scripture? In what ways might our own family histories influence our spiritual journeys and relationships with others?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'the Jebusite, and the Amorite, and the Girgasite,', 4, 53, 'connection', 'Nations in Scripture', 'The Jebusites, Amorites, and Girgasites are mentioned again in Joshua 3:10, where God commands Israel to take possession of the land. This connection highlights the ongoing conflict between the Israelites and these Canaanite nations, emphasizing God''s faithfulness in delivering the land to His people despite opposition.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Joshua 3:10", "description": "God''s instructions regarding the Canaanite nations"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'the Jebusite, and the Amorite, and the Girgasite,', 4, 53, 'theology', 'The Nature of God''s Judgment', 'This verse illustrates the concept of divine judgment as God distinguishes His chosen people from the Canaanite nations, which many scholars believe reflects God''s holiness and justice. The presence of these nations represents spiritual and moral opposition to God''s commandments, reinforcing the theme of separation between the sacred and the profane.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The New American Commentary, Genesis", "description": "Discussion on the implications of Canaanite nations"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'the Jebusite, and the Amorite, and the Girgasite,', 4, 53, 'question', 'Understanding Canaanite Influence', 'What lessons can we draw from the characteristics of the Jebusite, Amorite, and Girgasite regarding the influence of surrounding cultures on our faith? How might we identify and resist similar influences in our own lives today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'the Hivite, and the Arkite, and the Sinite,', 4, 47, 'connection', 'Canaanite Tribes Overview', 'The mention of the Hivites, Arkites, and Sinites connects to other lists of Canaanite tribes, illustrating the diverse groups that inhabited the land. For example, in Deuteronomy 7:1, God instructs Israel to drive out the seven nations, including the Hivites. This emphasizes the importance of distinguishing these tribes in understanding Israel''s conquest and the fulfillment of God''s promises.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 7:1", "description": "Lists the nations Israel is to dispossess, including the Hivites."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'the Hivite, and the Arkite, and the Sinite,', 4, 47, 'theology', 'Understanding Canaanite Idolatry', 'This passage highlights the presence of various Canaanite tribes, which many scholars believe were characterized by idolatrous practices. The Canaanites often worshiped Baal and Asherah, which posed a significant challenge to Israel''s faithfulness to Yahweh. Understanding their cultural context helps believers grasp the gravity of Israel''s covenant relationship with God, emphasizing the call to holiness and separation from pagan influences.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the implications of Israel''s interactions with Canaanite tribes."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'the Hivite, and the Arkite, and the Sinite,', 4, 47, 'question', 'Tribal Identities and Faithfulness', 'How does recognizing the distinct identities of the Hivites, Arkites, and Sinites challenge your understanding of cultural influences on faith? In what ways can you apply the lessons from Israel''s encounters with these tribes to your own life, especially regarding the influences that may tempt you away from your commitment to God?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And the Arvadite, and the Zemarite, and the Hamathite:', 0, 54, 'connection', 'Canaanite Tribes Reference', 'The mention of the Arvadite, Zemarite, and Hamathite connects to the broader theme of the Canaanite tribes, which is significant in understanding Israel''s later interactions with these nations. For example, in Joshua 13:4, we see the territory of the Canaanites defined, highlighting the ongoing historical and territorial implications stemming from these early genealogies.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Joshua 13:4", "description": "Describes the borders of the Canaanite territories."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'and afterward were the families of the Canaanites spread abroad.', 55, 119, 'theology', 'Divine Plan for Nations', 'This passage suggests that God''s plan encompasses the dispersion of nations, which aligns with the theological concept of divine sovereignty over human history. Many scholars believe that the scattering of the Canaanite families serves to fulfill God''s intentions for the earth to be populated and for diverse nations to emerge, as seen in Acts 17:26.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Acts 17:26", "description": "Discusses God''s role in determining boundaries and nations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And the Arvadite, and the Zemarite, and the Hamathite:', 0, 54, 'greek', 'Cultural Significance', 'Though the original text of Genesis is in Hebrew, the Greek translation (Septuagint) of these names provides insight into their cultural significance. The Greek term for ''Hamathite'' is Χαμαθίτης (Hamathitēs, G2263), referring to the ancient city of Hamath, which was known for its strong fortifications and strategic location, reflecting the historical importance of these tribes.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2263", "description": "Strong''s number for Hamathite."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'and afterward were the families of the Canaanites spread abroad.', 55, 119, 'question', 'Understanding Dispersion', 'What does it mean for families to be ''spread abroad'' in the context of God''s plans for humanity? How does this shaping of nations inform our understanding of community and diversity within the church today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'from Sidon, as thou comest to Gerar, unto Gaza;', 37, 84, 'connection', 'Geographical Significance', 'The mention of Sidon, Gerar, and Gaza connects with later biblical narratives, particularly in Joshua 11:8, where these locations play a role in the conquest of Canaan. This geographical context emphasizes the historical backdrop of the Canaanites'' territory and God''s promise to the Israelites concerning the land. Understanding these borders helps to frame the larger narrative of Israel''s journey and God''s providence.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Joshua 11:8", "description": "The conquest of Canaan and the significance of these locations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Sodom, and Gomorrah, and Admah, and Zeboim, even unto Lasha.', 105, 165, 'theology', 'Judgment and Mercy', 'The inclusion of Sodom and Gomorrah highlights themes of judgment and mercy in biblical theology. These cities, known for their wickedness, faced divine judgment (Genesis 19). Many scholars believe that this serves as a warning about the consequences of sin and the importance of righteousness, reminding readers of God''s holiness and justice.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on the judgment of Sodom and Gomorrah."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'the border of the Canaanites', 4, 32, 'question', 'Understanding Boundaries', 'What does ''the border of the Canaanites'' reveal about God''s plan for nations and the significance of land in Scripture? How might this understanding of territorial boundaries inform our view of God''s promises to His people today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Ham', 0, 25, 'connection', 'Sons of Ham Reference', 'The phrase ''sons of Ham'' connects to Genesis 9:22, where Ham is identified as the father of Canaan. This reference is significant as it establishes the lineage that will influence Israel''s history, particularly in the context of the Canaanites. Understanding this ancestry helps clarify the biblical narrative of Israel''s conquest of Canaan, as seen in the book of Joshua.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 9:22", "description": "Identifies Ham and his descendants'' role in biblical history."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'after their families', 27, 47, 'theology', 'Family Structure in Scripture', 'This passage suggests the importance of family and tribal identities in the biblical context. Many scholars believe that the organization of peoples into families and tribes reflects God''s design for community and governance among nations. This familial structure is foundational for understanding social dynamics in the Old Testament.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'after their tongues', 49, 68, 'greek', 'Language and Identity', 'שָׂפָה (safa, H8193) - tongue, language. The mention of ''tongues'' underscores the significance of language in shaping cultural identity. It indicates that each group had its own language, which played a crucial role in their societal structures and interactions. This concept of language as a marker of identity continues to resonate in discussions of cultural heritage.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8193", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for tongue/language."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'in their countries, and in their nations.', 70, 111, 'question', 'Nations and Divine Purpose', 'What does it mean for nations to be described as ''their countries''? How does this understanding of divinely ordained boundaries influence our view of modern nations? This reflection can lead to deeper insights about God''s sovereignty over nations and His purposes therein.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Unto Shem also, the father of all the children of Eber', 0, 54, 'connection', 'Lineage of Shem', 'This reference to Shem as the ''father of all the children of Eber'' is significant in tracing the lineage of the Hebrews. Cross-referencing with Genesis 11:10-26 reveals the genealogy leading to Abraham, highlighting God''s covenant with this line. Additionally, Hebrews 7:14 mentions Jesus as being from the tribe of Judah, tracing back to Shem''s descendants, emphasizing the continuity of God''s salvation plan through this lineage.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 11:10-26", "description": "Genealogy of Shem leading to Abraham."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 7:14", "description": "Jesus'' lineage connects to Shem."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'the father of all the children of Eber', 16, 54, 'theology', 'Significance of Eber', 'The mention of Eber is crucial as it is from his name that the term ''Hebrew'' is derived. Many scholars believe this highlights the identity of God''s chosen people. Eber''s descendants played a pivotal role in biblical history, and this lineage underscores God''s promise and faithfulness towards Israel, affirming the theological concept of a chosen people.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The New Bible Commentary", "description": "Analysis on the significance of Eber."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'the brother of Japheth the elder', 56, 88, 'question', 'Sibling Dynamics', 'What does it mean for Shem to be identified as ''the brother of Japheth the elder''? Reflecting on sibling relationships in Scripture, how might this familial connection influence the unfolding narrative of nations and peoples? Consider the implications of their distinctions and roles in God''s plan.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The children of Shem; Elam, and Asshur, and Arphaxad, and Lud, and Aram.', 0, 72, 'connection', 'Shem''s Lineage', 'The mention of Shem''s descendants connects to the broader narrative of the Table of Nations in Genesis 10, illustrating God''s unfolding plan through specific families. Elam, for instance, is referenced in Isaiah 11:11, revealing its significance in later biblical history. Asshur, associated with the Assyrian Empire, plays a critical role in Israel''s prophetic literature, especially in relation to judgment and exile (Amos 6:2). Understanding these connections enriches our comprehension of biblical history and God''s sovereignty.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Isaiah 11:11", "description": "Elam''s future restoration is prophesied."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Amos 6:2", "description": "Asshur''s significance in Israel''s narrative."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The children of Shem; Elam, and Asshur, and Arphaxad, and Lud, and Aram.', 0, 72, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Lineage', 'This verse highlights God''s sovereignty in choosing specific lineages to fulfill His covenant promises. Many scholars believe that the emphasis on Shem''s descendants reflects God''s plan for redemption through the lineage leading to Abraham and ultimately to Christ. This underscores the theological concept that God''s purposes are often worked out through particular people and families, illustrating His divine providence throughout history.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Elam, and Asshur, and Arphaxad, and Lud, and Aram.', 22, 72, 'greek', 'Significance of Elam', 'אֵילָם (Elam, H5867) - a region located in modern-day Iran, known for its ancient civilization. Elam is significant not only as a geographical reference but also in prophetic contexts, where its people are mentioned in relation to the fate of Israel. Understanding its historical and geographical context enriches our interpretation of biblical prophecies.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5867", "description": "Strong''s number for Elam."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'The children of Shem; Elam, and Asshur, and Arphaxad, and Lud, and Aram.', 0, 72, 'question', 'Reflecting on Lineage', 'What does it mean for us today to consider the specific lineages mentioned in Scripture? How does recognizing God''s choice of particular families to fulfill His plans shape our understanding of His work in our own lives and communities?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the children of Aram; Uz, and Hul, and Gether, and Mash.', 0, 60, 'connection', 'Geographical Significance', 'The names of Aram''s children, particularly Uz, have notable mentions in the Bible. For instance, Job is described as being from the land of Uz (Job 1:1), which links this region to the story of suffering and faith. Additionally, the mention of Aram ties to the broader narrative of nations and their descendants, reflecting God''s plan for humanity''s development through these lineages (Genesis 10:22-24).', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Job 1:1", "description": "Job''s origin ties Uz to significant biblical narratives."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 10:22-24", "description": "Context of the descendants of Shem and their importance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the children of Aram; Uz, and Hul, and Gether, and Mash.', 0, 60, 'theology', 'Divine Heritage', 'The mention of Aram''s descendants suggests the unfolding of God''s plan through generations. Many scholars believe this genealogy reflects the establishment of nations and cultures, emphasizing that God is active in human history, shaping peoples and destinies. This theological perspective invites readers to reflect on God''s sovereignty over all nations and His purpose in their development.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the children of Aram; Uz, and Hul, and Gether, and Mash.', 0, 60, 'question', 'Reflection on Lineage', 'How does understanding the lineage of nations, such as those descended from Aram, influence our view of God''s plan for humanity? In what ways does this prompt us to consider our own heritage and its role in God''s overarching story?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'And Arphaxad begat Salah;', 0, 25, 'connection', 'Lineage Connection', 'The genealogy presented here connects directly to the broader narrative of God''s covenant with Abraham, as seen in Genesis 12:1-3. This lineage is crucial as it shows the unfolding of God''s plan through specific descendants, emphasizing the significance of family lines in biblical history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:1-3", "description": "God''s covenant with Abraham, highlighting the importance of lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'and Salah begat Eber.', 26, 47, 'theology', 'Importance of Eber', 'Many scholars believe that Eber is significant as the ancestor of the Hebrews, which ties into the identity of Israel as God''s chosen people. Eber''s name is often associated with the term ''Hebrew,'' indicating a special role in the unfolding narrative of salvation history.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 10:21-31", "description": "Commentary on genealogies and their theological significance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'And Arphaxad begat Salah; and Salah begat Eber.', 0, 47, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Heritage', 'What does it mean for us to be part of a divine lineage through faith, as seen in the genealogy from Arphaxad to Eber? How does recognizing this heritage influence our understanding of our identity in Christ?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'for in his days was the earth divided;', 61, 99, 'connection', 'Division of the Earth', 'The phrase ''for in his days was the earth divided'' can be linked to Genesis 11:1, where the whole earth had one language and a common speech. This connection is significant as it highlights a pivotal moment in human history when God intervened to scatter humanity across the earth, leading to the formation of diverse nations and languages. It also reflects God''s sovereignty in human affairs.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 11:1", "description": "Describes the unity of language before Babel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'Eber were born two sons: the name of one was Peleg;', 9, 60, 'theology', 'Significance of Eber and Peleg', 'Many scholars believe that Eber represents the Hebrew people, and Peleg''s name, which means ''division,'' reflects a significant theological theme of separation and the establishment of nations. This passage suggests that God''s plan involved the diversification of humanity, which is essential for understanding the unfolding of biblical history, especially regarding God''s covenant with Israel.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Wenham, Gordon J. Genesis 1-15. Word Biblical Commentary.", "description": "Explores the genealogies and their theological implications."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'And unto Eber were born two sons:', 0, 33, 'question', 'Reflection on Lineage', 'What does the mention of Eber''s two sons reveal about God''s intention for families and nations? How might understanding the significance of lineage in biblical times shape our perspective on our own family heritage and responsibilities today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'his brother’s name was Joktan.', 104, 134, 'greek', 'Etymology of Joktan', 'Although this text is in Hebrew, the name ''Joktan'' (H3355) could be explored in terms of its root meaning, which is often associated with ''little'' or ''small.'' This insight can reflect on the theme of humility and the unexpected ways God can work through those who may seem insignificant.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3355", "description": "Strong''s number for Joktan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'And Joktan begat Almodad, and Sheleph, and Hazarmaveth, and Jerah,', 0, 66, 'connection', 'Genealogy Significance', 'Joktan''s lineage is significant as it connects to the broader narrative of human dispersal following the Tower of Babel (Genesis 11:1-9). The names listed can also be seen as a precursor to the nations that emerge later in the biblical narrative, illustrating God''s plan for diversity among peoples. This connection emphasizes the theme of God’s sovereignty in human history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 11:1-9", "description": "The account of the Tower of Babel, illustrating the dispersion of nations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Almodad', 17, 24, 'greek', 'Name Meaning', 'The name ''Almodad'' is thought to be derived from a root meaning ''to be rich'' or ''to be strong'', although it is primarily a Hebrew name (H5904). This reflects the cultural context in which names often conveyed significant meanings related to character or destiny.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5904", "description": "Strong''s Hebrew number related to the name Almodad."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 10, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'and Hazarmaveth', 39, 54, 'theology', 'Cultural Diversity', 'The mention of Hazarmaveth suggests the early formation of distinct cultures and peoples. Many scholars believe this reflects the theological concept that God desires a diverse creation, as seen in Revelation 7:9, where people from every nation worship together. This diversity enriches the understanding of God''s kingdom.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Revelation 7:9", "description": "A vision of a diverse multitude worshiping before the throne of God."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
